******
[1] Guangxi Autonomous Region
Date: Fri 7 Feb 2014
Source: South China Morning Post [edited]
http://www.scmp.com/news/china/article/1422473/un-agency-warns-risk-bird-flu-crossing-chinas-borders-grows


The proliferation of the H7N9 bird flu virus among poultry in live-bird markets in Guangxi [Autonomous Region] has "significantly increased the risk" that it will spread to neighbouring countries, a United Nations agency warned. The Food and Agriculture Organisation yesterday [6 Feb 2014] urged countries sharing a border with China to review their emergency preparations and response plans to address a possible outbreak. "The current situation in Guangxi will require a renewed vigilance to mitigate the effects of cross-border spread," it said. Its warning came after the province reported 2 human cases of H7N9 on Tuesday [4 Feb 2014], involving a 5 year old boy and his 41 year old mother.

Guangxi, which shares a border with Viet Nam, was where the Chinese authorities tracked movement of the H7N9 infection to live-bird markets between [24 and 28 Jan 2014]. It was also where the 1st human casualty was reported. Neighbouring Yunnan shares borders with Viet Nam, Myanmar, and Laos. China's national health commission said there was no proof that H7N9 was spreading sustainably from person to person, but it could not rule out the possibility of "limited" human-to-human infections.

There have been at least 290 confirmed human H7N9 cases and 66 deaths in the mainland, Hong Kong, and Taiwan. Beijing, Guangdong, and Hunan each reported a new human case of H7N9 yesterday [6 Feb 2014], while Jiangsu reported 2, the Xinhua News agency said. All patients had been exposed to poultry except the Guangdong case, but there were no details about how the Foshan [Guangdong] woman, 36, contracted the virus.

The fact that the virus produced no detectable symptoms among infected birds had seriously disrupted poultry production and markets, the UN said, adding that close contact between infected poultry and humans -- particularly during festivals such as the Lunar New Year [31 Jan 2014] -- presented a serious health risk.

Despite the risk, there was no evidence that the virus was present in Vie Nam or any of China's other neighbouring countries in Southeast Asia. But there were indications, based on experience with the H5N1 virus, that H7N9 was easily capable of crossing borders. A 3 week ban on live chicken sales is in effect in Hong Kong until [18 Feb 2014] after H7N9 was found in a live chicken from the mainland. University of Hong Kong microbiologist Ho Pak-leung said poultry exposure was the main cause of human infections and warned the public to avoid contact with live poultry.

[byline: Emily Tsang]

